Introduction¶

For this Data Analyst project, I selected the TMDB Dataset to investigate.

Question Researched:¶

  1. What is the affect of runtime over popularity?
  2. Film count changes over year?
  3. Movie Popularity over year
  4. Genres Popularity over year?
  5. Which genres are most popular from year to year
  6. Mean Revenues for All Genres

Data Cleaning¶

  1. Drop unnecessary columns : tagline, keywords, homepage, tagline, imdb_id, overview,budget_adj, revenue_adj.
  2. Drop null value rows for: production_companies, cast, director, and genres.
  3. Replace zero values with null for : budget and revenue columns.
  4. Drop duplicates.
Drop unnecessary columns¶
In [852]:
#drop columns with inplace
df.drop(['tagline', 'imdb_id', 'homepage', 'tagline', 'overview', 'keywords', 'budget_adj', 'revenue_adj'], axis=1, inplace=True)
Drop null value for columns¶
In [853]:
df.dropna(subset=['director','genres', 'production_companies','cast'], inplace=True)
Replace zero values with null¶
In [854]:
df['budget'] = df['budget'].replace(0, np.NaN)
df['revenue'] = df['revenue'].replace(0, np.NaN)

I now that, this operation will effect efficiency bad. But we can not fill zero values with any of the methods we have learned.

Drop duplicates¶
In [855]:
df.drop_duplicates(keep='first', inplace=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Question 1 : What is the affect of runtime over popularity?¶

First, lets draw a line chart, including runtime and popularity

In [858]:
ax = df.groupby('runtime').popularity.mean().plot(kind='line', title ="Runtime Count over Film Popularity", figsize=(15, 10), legend=True, fontsize=12)
ax.set_xlabel("Runtime", fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel("Popularity", fontsize=12)
plt.show()

Lets smooth the chart with moving-average

In [859]:
ax = df.groupby('runtime').popularity.mean().rolling(window=25).mean().plot(kind='line', title ="Runtime Count over Film Popularity", figsize=(15, 10), legend=True, fontsize=12)
ax.set_xlabel("Runtime", fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel("Popularity", fontsize=12)
plt.show()

expand_str = df["genres"].str.split('|', expand=True)
dummies_df = pd.get_dummies(expand_str.stack(dropna=False)).sum(level=0).add_prefix("genres_")
df = pd.concat([df, dummies_df], axis=1, join_axes=[df.index])

Question 6 : Mean Revenues for All Genres¶

First lets draw a line chart for revenue over genres

#df[df.columns[pd.Series(df.columns).str.startswith('genres_')]].columns
revenue_df = pd.DataFrame(index=['revenue'])
for str in df.columns:
    if str.startswith('genres_'):
        revenue_df[str]=df[(df[str] == True)].revenue.mean()


ax = revenue_df.plot(kind='bar', title ="Revenues On Genres", figsize=(15, 10), legend=True, fontsize=12)
ax.set_xlabel("Genres", fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel("AVG Revenue", fontsize=12)

Conclusions¶

Question 1 : What is the affect of runtime over popularity? : We can clearly see that close to 200 runtimes has the highest popularity. Which means: we can say that increase or decrease of this runtime has a negative effect on popularity.

Question 2 : Film count changes over year?: We can see that film counts increasing over years. Also We can see a slight decrease in movie counts due to global economic crysis (ref):

  • the big world economic crisis in 2008/2009.
  • dotcom bubble crisis in 1999/2000.
  • Asia crisis in 1997.

Question 3 : Movie Popularity over year : We can say that the popularity of the movies has increased slowly since 2000 and then increased more rapidly.

The most important reason for this may be the exponential increase in internet usage. As described here; The popularity score is calculated by the following criterias.

  • Number of votes for the day
  • Number of views for the day
  • Number of users who marked it as a "favourite" for the day
  • Number of users who added it to their "watchlist" for the day
  • Release date
  • Number of total votes
  • Previous days score

Question 4 : Genres Popularity over year? : While most genres have constant popularity, we can say Action, Adventure and History Genres had a nice rise.

Question 5 : Which genres are most popular from year to year : We can clearly see, Fantasy, Adventure and Science Fiction genres lead last years.

Question 6 : Mean Revenues for All Genres : Animation, Fantasy and Science Fiction have most revenue.
